  <a name="planning"></a>
  <h1>
    Planning
  </h1>

  <h2>
    Semantics
  </h2>

  <p>
    Within the first month, we redefined the concept of "teams." I had a working 
    theory that Pros could be considered as teams, albeit not within the same 
    company. Supported by research and data, I drafted a definition to 
    distinguish between "uppercase-T Teams" and "lowercase-T teams." Together 
    with my cross-functional partners, we established and promoted these new 
    semantics.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      An uppercase-t "Team" is people working at the same company.
    </li>
    <li>
      A lowercase-t "team" is a group of people working together towards a goal.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These new semantics helped us explore a wider breadth of problems and 
    solutions since we were now looking at more relationships than previously.
  </p>

  <h2>
    Validation Framework
  </h2>

  <p>
    Besides opening new avenues for exploration, we had to tackle a validation 
    gap. Around six months into the project, we terminated one of our 
    workstreams, considering it a failure. We encountered internal obstacles, 
    skipped crucial validation steps, and overcommitted our team. Our lengthy 
    timelines and substantial technological investments resulted in significant 
    time wasted. To address this issue, I drafted an initial version of an 
    incremental validation framework to prevent excessive investment. I assigned 
    ownership of this framework to an EPD trio within the group to share 
    responsibility, iterate, validate, and scale it.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this framework, each stage would have a time box to limit scope. The 
    size of the audience required for conviction would depend on the level of 
    risk. We would scale the audience and investment only when we had sufficient 
    conviction. This approach proved effective, providing a staged framework for 
    investment through validation.
  </p>
</article>

