<article class="content content--reading post">
  <a name="designing"></a>
  <h1>
    Designing
  </h1>

  <p>
    The solution can be presented in three parts: a fail, a win, and a learning. 
    Our initial attempt at a "Teams-first" solution failed. However, our 
    "Pro-first" solution achieved an incremental win. It was our final solution, 
    combining "Teams and Pro" based on our learnings, that proved to be a 
    success and shaped our future strategy. I would like to share these three 
    parts of our solution because the combination of a fail, a win, and a 
    learning yielded the best outcome.
  </p>

  <p>
    We used a double diamond approach for the squads working on this project, 
    exploring different time constraints and incorporating the Feature 
    Validation framework and S.P.Ps. Ongoing discovery allowed us to iterate 
    quickly and address small, validated problems with our solutions.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-activation-double-diamond.png" %>
      <figcaption>
        The double diamond design thinking process popularized by the British Design Council.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <h2>
    Part I
  </h2>

  <p>
    <strong>During the discovery phase</strong>, our lead group researcher took 
    charge. As a domain expert, she guided new research, facilitated customer 
    connections, and provided existing studies. Additionally, we initiated a 
    "Team Types" study to gain insights into the composition of both uppercase-T 
    Teams and lowercase-T teams. I personally requested and sponsored this 
    study, which would be conducted midway through the project.
  </p>

  <p>
    As the squad moved from discovery to define, they began to hone in on the 
    problems they wanted to solve for. The "Teams-first" squad defined two 
    problems:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      Teams are concerned about freelancers accessing sensitive company 
      information.
    </li>
    <li>
      There are multiple sources of truth when working with Freelancers.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    After a few weeks and several rounds of user testing, the concept of the 
    "client space" emerged. A workspace designated for collaboration between a 
    company and a freelancer.
  </p>
</article>

