<article class="content content--reading post">
  <p>
    However, during the development process, we encountered internal obstacles 
    and found that there was overlap in our proposed solutions. As a result, 
    the "client space" became overly simplified.
  </p>

  <p>
    The prolonged design process, internal conflicts, and collaboration 
    challenges with another team resulted in a delayed launch of the "client 
    space." Despite compromises made and technical complexities encountered, it 
    took approximately six months to ship the product. However, feedback from 
    the testing group and customers was negative, as the "client space" was 
    perceived as indistinguishable from a shared folder and lacked perceived 
    value. Nevertheless, valuable insights were gained from extensive customer 
    conversations. We learned the importance of framing, the broader scope of 
    security concerns, and the ongoing issue of content ownership during 
    collaboration. Furthermore, we began uncovering different types of working 
    relationships.
  </p>

  <h2>
    Part II
  </h2>

  <p>
    While we were learning on one front, we simultaneously pursued a different 
    approach with another squad. The Pro-first squad focused on distinct 
    problems, resulting in a different outcome. However, this squad consisted of 
    a senior product designer, Paula Barcante, and lacked a product manager. 
    Despite the absence of a product partner, Paula took the lead in defining 
    the problem and solution space, with my support. We engaged in daily working 
    sessions, conducted co-competitive audits, engaged in strategic writing and 
    critique sessions, and more.
  </p>

  <p>
    Paula assumed responsibility for bi-weekly updates with cross-functional 
    leads, as she directed the allocation of 10 team members' time. A product 
    partner was hired approximately two months into the project. Early on, 
    Paula outlined the following problem spaces:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      Professionals don't have access to the tools their clients have, 
      preventing collaboration.
    </li>
    <li>
      Professionals wanted to appear professional when working with clients.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    <strong>During the develop phase</strong> the squad explored a wide range 
    of solution spaces: granting Pros access to Team's features, sharing third 
    party tools, collaborative project management, and integrations with third 
    party delivery and presentation tools.
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>The first solution the team delivered was Password Sharing.</strong> 
    The squad shipped a feature in our Passwords product where an admin could 
    set up a collection of passwords of third party tools and invite a 
    freelancer to that collection. With one invite, a Pro had access to all the 
    tools the Team had.
  </p>
</article>

