<article class="content content--reading post">
  <h2>
    Part III
  </h2>

  <p>
    Through these projects, research, and experimentation, I made an 
    observation: we had been approaching collaboration as a single transaction, 
    focusing on behaviors like one-off sharing and file access. However, we 
    should have been considering the various forms of collaboration as a series 
    of behaviors within relationships.
  </p>
  <p>
    Around six months into the project, I tasked the Product Designers and 
    Product Managers from the squads to map out relationships using our 
    behavioral data and the insights from our Team Types research. This mapping 
    would serve as a guide for our solution.
  </p>

  <div class="work-image-container">
    <figure class="work-image">
      <%= image_tag "works/dropbox-collaboration-flexible-membership-map.png" %>
      <figcaption>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </div>

  <p>
    <strong>As we moved into our define phase</strong> the squad and leadership 
    agreed that the original problems were still unsolved and worth solving. 
    We stuck to the same problems but with new solution space guidance.
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li>
      Teams are concerned about freelancers accessing sensitive company 
      information.
    </li>
    <li>
      There are multiple sources of truth when working with Freelancers.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    In our develop phase, guided by prioritizing relationships, the Teams squad 
    introduced the concept of "flexible membership." To mitigate overinvestment 
    risks, we implemented the Feature Validation and Stop Pivot Preserve 
    frameworks. Our initial phase involved concept testing with 20 users, 
    prioritizing customer value over solution functionality or usability. We 
    shared concepts like secure workspaces, time-limited access, and sharing 
    features with customers.
  </p>
  <p>
    The concepts that resonated included time constraints, access management, 
    and onboarding/offboarding processes. This led to the development of a 
    "guest pass" solutionâ€”a new type of license. Security was entrusted to the 
    Team, granting the Pro access to the necessary resources for a specific 
    duration. Introducing a new license type carried significant risk, requiring 
    substantial technical investment and a challenging decision to make with 
    customers. Recognizing the need for thorough validation, we created a beta 
    version for A/B testing. Although the version had unresolved edge cases and 
    untouched platforms, it served as a testable solution. Surprisingly, it was 
    well received.
  </p>
</article>

