<article class="content content--reading post">
  <a name="impact"></a>
  <h1>
    The Impact
  </h1>

  <p>
    With the launch of Branding and password sharing, we observed a moderate 
    2.4% relative lift in 60-day retention, indicating improved user engagement 
    and retention rates. The testing of the guest passes immediately gained 
    traction demonstrating its value and appeal to users. The introduction of it 
    also opened new doors for Dropbox's revenue model, moving beyond traditional 
    SKUs and bundles. By connecting existing users with flexible licenses, we 
    successfully tapped into a new market segment, generating additional revenue 
    streams while addressing customer needs effectively.
  </p>

  <a name="challenges"></a>
  <h1>
    The Challenges
  </h1>

  <p>
    Acknowledging our overcommitment without sufficient validation transformed 
    our approach to experimentation. By incorporating decision-making guidance 
    and accountability touchpoints, we improved our work process. Our openness 
    about our failure prompted others to embrace our framework, eager to avoid 
    similar pitfalls and improve their own outcomes.
  </p>

  <a name="closing"></a>
  <h1>
    Closing
  </h1>

  <p>
    In mid-2021, our "Teams Group" tackled declining Teams SKU retention and 
    increased purchases of the "Professional" SKU for freelancers. Through a 
    fail, a win, and a learning approach, we implemented validation frameworks, 
    adapted design thinking processes, and delivered successful solutions like 
    password sharing and branded sharing. Our innovative "guest passes" as a new 
    license type tapped into a new market segment, improving user engagement, 
    retention rates, and revenue. These efforts established a valuable framework 
    for experimentation and decision-making within the organization.
  </p>
</article>